Grammar of graphics

ggplot is based on the Grammar of graphics. This grammar uses a number of building blocks that are added together to create custom, publication quality figures (similar to piping several dplyr verbs together). The key features that make ggplot preferable over base R graphics are:

  • pretty default settings
  • automatic legends, colors, and facets
  • built in statistical overlays like regressions lines and smoothers
  • can pipe dplyr/tidyr modified data directly into ggplot functions

However, please be aware that it can sometimes be difficult and certainly frustrating to use ggplot alone to get the exact figure you want. It usually gets you 99% of the way there though.

The grammar of ggplot includes:

  • data: 2D data frame of variables
  • aesthetics: map variables to visual attributes
  • geoms: graphical representation of data (points, lines, etc.)
  • stats: statistical transformations
  • scales: control how to map a variable to an aesthetic
  • facets: juxtapose mini-plots of data subsets, split by variable(s)
  • guides: axes, legend, etc. reflect the variables and their values

Dot plots

The base function of any plot from ggplot is unsurprisingly the ggplot function. This function takes in the data and basic aesthetics of the plot, like the x- and y-axis variables, but does not specify the way in which you want to plot the data (like dots, bars, etc.). So, if we try to plot depth by oxygen (O2) with just ggplot, we get a plot with the correct axes but no actual data.

ggplot(metadata, aes(x=O2_uM, y=Depth_m))

To add in the data, we must specify a geom. To get a dot plot, we will use geom_point. Notice that we dont need to pass any variables to the geom function. This is because when not specified within the geom, ggplot takes these data from the base ggplot function.

ggplot(metadata, aes(x=O2_uM, y=Depth_m)) +
  geom_point()

So, the above is equivalent to

ggplot(metadata) +
  geom_point(aes(x=O2_uM, y=Depth_m))

Color, shape, size

We can change the color (outline and fill), shape, or size of our points by continuing to modify the aesthetics.

ggplot(metadata, aes(x=O2_uM, y=Depth_m, color="blue")) +
  geom_point()

But wait! Thats not blue! What happened?

What happened is geoms cannot get all of their data from the ggplot function. Within ggplot, you can specify attributes that are part of the overall plot (everything that shows up if you only use ggplot, no geom) but not attributes associated with a specific geom. In this case, the dots are there because of geom_point so we must change their color within the geom function.

ggplot(metadata, aes(x=O2_uM, y=Depth_m)) +
  geom_point(color="blue")

The same holds for changing shape and size such as in

ggplot(metadata, aes(x=O2_uM, y=Depth_m)) +
  geom_point(shape="square")

ggplot(metadata, aes(x=O2_uM, y=Depth_m)) +
  geom_point(size=10)

We can also add a third variable to our plot by including it as color, shape, or size of dots. This works for both continuous and categorical variables.

Lets see if the oxygen measurement in volts correlates with measurements in \(\mu\)M. In this case, we will need a legend, which is part of the base ggplot so we must include size within the geom instead of the base ggplot. When it comes to where to put aesthetics in ggplot vs.a geom, trial and error are usually the way to go.

ggplot(metadata, aes(x=O2_uM, y=Depth_m, size=OxygenSBE_V)) +
  geom_point()

Unsurprisingly, oxygen concentrations in both units correlate with each other.

gglot with phyloseq

Another package that plays nice with ggplot is phyloseq, which is designed to complete alpha- and beta-diversity analyses as well as visualization of sequencing data. As stated in the introduction, we have already created a phyloseq object for your use today.

physeq
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 4368 taxa and 7 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 7 samples by 22 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 4368 taxa by 7 taxonomic ranks ]
## phy_tree()    Phylogenetic Tree: [ 4368 tips and 4366 internal nodes ]

This is the bacterial 16S OTU sequence data associated with 7 of the depths within our geochemical metadata. We see that this phyloseq object contains

  • OTU table for 4368 OTUs across the 7 samples
  • Metadata (called sample data)
  • Taxonomy table denoting the classifications of all of the 4368 OTUs
  • Phylogenetic tree detailing the the relatedness of all 4368 OTUs

What makes it worth it to use phyloseq is its inherent understanding of taxonomy. So instead of writing a complex mutate function to, say, add together all OTUs at the phylum level, we can just use phyloseq to do that.

phyloseq plot functions mirror ggplot like plot_bar = geom_bar. For example, we can plot the phylum level communities by depth by simply specifying the fill.

plot_bar(physeq, fill="Phylum")

This would not work in ggplot without phyloseq because ggplot does not understand a phyloseq object or its pieces.

However, when we look at this plot, we see that we have a different total number of sequences (Abundance) in each sample. So, our bars do not all go up to the same level.

We could use mutate from dplyr to modify our OTU table to be percentages and then reform the phyloseq object for plotting. But since this is a common problem and dplyr is difficult to use directly on a phyloseq object, phyloseq has the function transform_sample_counts just for this purpose.

So, we can calculate a percentage of the total of each sample for each OTU with the following. The function applies the equation we give it (100*x/sum(x)) to every cell in our OTU table.

physeq_percent = transform_sample_counts(physeq, function(x) 100 * x/sum(x))

Now, when we plot the phyla, we see 0-100% for all samples.

plot_bar(physeq_percent, fill="Phylum")

But this still isnt a great plot. There are black lines separating each OTU within a bar. This is great for highly abundant OTUs but creates wholly black regions when many low abundance OTUs are next to each other such that you can no longer see the phylum colors.

To remedy this, we add a geom from ggplot. By specifying stat as identity instead of the default stat_count, R no longer sees the OTUs as separate data and therefore, the separating lines do not occur.

plot_bar(physeq_percent, fill="Phylum") + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill=Phylum), stat="identity")

Faceting

Another great feature of ggplot is faceting. We see in our stacked bar plots above that some low abundance taxa are so low that you cant see them and some colors are so similar that its difficult to tell them apart.

When you have complex data like this, you can separate it into multiple panels (or facets) to more clearly see patterns. Working from our previous bar plot, we simply add face_wrap and tell it what variable to separate by.

plot_bar(physeq_percent, fill="Phylum") +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=Phylum), stat="identity") +
  facet_wrap(~Phylum)

However, since we have very variable abundance values, the default which forces all y-axes to be on the same scale doesnt really work for us. We can let R scale independently in each panel with the scales parameter like so.

We also dont really need a legend anymore because each facet it labeled. So we can remove this in the theme.

plot_bar(physeq_percent, fill="Phylum") +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=Phylum), stat="identity") +
  facet_wrap(~Phylum, scales="free_y") +
  theme(legend.position="none")

Now we can clearly see how each phylum changes with depth.
